 European Language Charter -- t10. Metadiversity, or the Uniqueness of the Lambs -- t11. Division of Responsibility in Karelian and Veps Language Revitalisation Discourse -- t12. Standard Language Ideology and Minority Languages: The Case of the Permian Languages -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAre we facing an immense wave of language death or a period of remarkable new linguistic variation? Or both? This book answers this question by analysing studies of language endangerment and loss along with those of language change, revitalization and diversity. Using case studies from Russia and the EU, the authors compare historical language variation to that of the present day, arguing that accelerated language extinction can be considered a result of colonization, modernization and globalization, but so too can many new creoles, intertwined and mixed languages, new ethnic identities, new groups of urban dwellers or migrant groups, all with their own distinct cultural traits. The book therefore surmises that the linguistic heritage of today is simultaneously more endangered and more diverse than ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCode switching (Linguistics) 0aCode switching (Linguistics). 0aEndangered languages. 0aHistorical linguistics. 0aLanguage and languagesxVariation. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLanguage change.  aLanguage death.  aLanguage endangerment.  aLanguage extinction.  aLanguage revitalisation.  aLanguage variation.  aMinorities.  aPlurilingualism.  aSociolinguistics.  aSuperdiversity.1 aEdygarova, Svetlana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanurik, Boglárka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/